The boot chain in detail — GRUB, initramfs, systemd.

Now let's fill in the detail behind the hook. Between pressing power and seeing a login prompt, there are four well-defined stages, and knowing them is exactly what lets you fix a machine that won't boot.

Stage one is the firmware, BIOS or UEFI. When you power on, the motherboard's firmware runs first; you don't choose it, the hardware does. It runs the power-on self-test, a basic hardware check, and then finds a boot device. Legacy BIOS loads the first five hundred and twelve bytes of the disk, the master boot record, and jumps to that code. Modern UEFI instead reads a small EFI system partition, usually mounted at slash-boot-slash-efi, and runs a dot-e-f-i bootloader file from it. You can tell which you're on: if the directory slash-sys-slash-firmware-slash-efi exists, you booted UEFI; if not, BIOS.

Stage two is GRUB, the bootloader on virtually every Linux system. It presents a menu if there's more than one OS, then loads the chosen kernel into memory. Now, an important warning: do not edit slash-boot-slash-grub-slash-grub-dot-cfg directly, because that file is generated. You edit slash-etc-slash-default-slash-grub, and the scripts in slash-etc-slash-grub-dot-d, and then run update-grub to regenerate it. Handy knobs there include GRUB-TIMEOUT and GRUB-CMDLINE-LINUX. And at the menu itself, you can press the letter e to edit an entry for just one boot, which is your escape hatch when a config change breaks normal booting.

Stage three: the kernel and the initramfs. GRUB loads two files. The kernel, vmlinuz, is Linux itself. The initramfs, initrd-dot-img, is a tiny in-memory filesystem containing just enough drivers and tools to find and mount your real root filesystem. Why does it exist? Because your root might sit on an LVM volume, on an encrypted disk, on a RAID array, and the kernel needs those drivers and tools before it can possibly mount slash. The initramfs provides them, and once the real root is mounted, it's discarded. You rebuild it with update-initramfs dash-u on Debian, or dracut dash-f on Red Hat.

And stage four is systemd. The kernel executes slash-sbin-slash-init, which on every modern distro is a symlink to systemd, as process ID one. From there systemd takes over, starts all the services, and reaches the default target, which means everything's ready, here's your login prompt. And that fourth stage is where the rest of this module lives.
